In C#, you can make HTTP requests using various classes provided by the .NET framework. Here are a few common approaches:

1. Using HttpClient (recommended for modern .NET applications):

```csharp
using System.Net.Http;
using System.Threading.Tasks;

class Program
{
    static async Task Main(string[] args)
    {
        using (var client = new HttpClient())
        {
            string url = "https://api.example.com/data";
            HttpResponseMessage response = await client.GetAsync(url);

            if (response.IsSuccessStatusCode)
            {
                string responseBody = await response.Content.ReadAsStringAsync();
                Console.WriteLine(responseBody);
            }
        }
    }
}
```

2. Using WebClient (older, but still functional):

```csharp
using System.Net;

class Program
{
    static void Main(string[] args)
    {
        using (var client = new WebClient())
        {
            string url = "https://api.example.com/data";
            string responseBody = client.DownloadString(url);
            Console.WriteLine(responseBody);
        }
    }
}
```

3. Using HttpWebRequest (lowest level, gives more control):

```csharp
using System.Net;
using System.IO;

class Program
{
    static void Main(string[] args)
    {
        string url = "https://api.example.com/data";
        HttpWebRequest request = (HttpWebRequest)WebRequest.Create(url);

        using (HttpWebResponse response = (HttpWebResponse)request.GetResponse())
        using (Stream stream = response.GetResponseStream())
        using (StreamReader reader = new StreamReader(stream))
        {
            string responseBody = reader.ReadToEnd();
            Console.WriteLine(responseBody);
        }
    }
}
```

For each of these methods, you can customize the request by setting headers, changing the HTTP method (GET, POST, etc.), adding request bodies, and handling different types of responses.

The HttpClient approach is generally recommended for new development as it provides a modern, easy-to-use API and supports asynchronous operations out of the box.

Remember to handle exceptions and dispose of resources properly in your actual implementation. Also, consider using async/await for better performance and responsiveness in your application.

