To get the context of the MainActivity from within a static method, you can create a static property in your MainActivity class to hold the context and set it in the OnCreate method. Then, you can access this static property from any static method.

Here's an example:

```csharp
public class MainActivity : AppCompatActivity
{
    public static Context Context { get; private set; }

    protected override void OnCreate(Bundle savedInstanceState)
    {
        base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);
        SetContentView(Resource.Layout.activity_main);

        Context = this; // Set the static Context property
    }

    // Rest of your MainActivity code...
}
```

Now, you can access the MainActivity's context from any static method using `MainActivity.Context`. For example:

```csharp
public static class SomeClass
{
    public static void SomeStaticMethod()
    {
        var context = MainActivity.Context;
        // Use the context here...
    }
}
```

By setting the static `Context` property in the `OnCreate` method of your MainActivity, you ensure that the context is available as soon as the activity is created.

Please note that this approach assumes that your MainActivity is the entry point of your application and is always created before any static methods that require the context are called. If you have multiple activities or a different application structure, you may need to adapt this approach accordingly.

