1. Use a Singleton class:
Create a Singleton class that holds a reference to the current activity context. In the constructor, set the context using `Activity.FindViewById<MainActivity>(Resource.Id.main_activity)`. Then, from within the static method, you can call `MainActivity.Instance.Context` to get the current activity context.
Here's an example:
```csharp
public class ActivityContextManager
{
    private static ActivityContext _context;

    private ActivityContextManager()
    {
        // Set the context of the current activity
        _context = Activity.FindViewById<MainActivity>(Resource.Id.main_activity).Context;
    }

    public static Context Instance
    {
        get
        {
            return _context;
        }
    }
```
2. Use a WeakReference:

Create a field in your class that holds a weak reference to the current activity context. In the constructor, set the context using `Activity.FindViewById<MainActivity>(Resource.Id.main_activity)`. Then, from within the static method, you can call `MainActivity.Context` to get the current activity context.
Here's an example:
```csharp
public class ActivityContextManager
{
    private readonly WeakReference<Context> _context;

    private ActivityContextManager()
    {
        // Set the context of the current activity
        _context = new WeakReference<Context>(Activity.FindViewById<MainActivity>(Resource.Id.main_activity).Context);
    }

    public static Context Instance
    {
        get
        {
            return _context.Target as Context;
        }
    }
```
3. Use a Dependency Injection framework:

You can use a Dependency Injection framework like Dagger or Koin to provide the context of the current activity to your class. In the constructor of your class, inject the context using a provider. Then, from within the static method, you can call `Context.getApplicationContext()` to get the current activity context.
