Here's a Java program that solves the Steam Tunnels problem:

```java
import java.io.File;
import java.io.FileNotFoundException;
import java.util.*;

public class Tunnels {
    public static void main(String[] args) throws FileNotFoundException {
        Scanner scanner = new Scanner(new File("tunnels.dat"));
        int N = Integer.parseInt(scanner.nextLine());

        for (int i = 0; i < N; i++) {
            String line = scanner.nextLine();
            String[] parts = line.split("[{}]");

            // Parse buildings
            Set<String> buildings = new HashSet<>(Arrays.asList(parts[1].split(",")));

            // Parse tunnels
            Map<String, Set<String>> tunnels = new HashMap<>();
            for (int j = 2; j < parts.length; j += 2) {
                if (parts[j].isEmpty()) continue;
                String[] connection = parts[j].split(",");
                tunnels.computeIfAbsent(connection[0], k -> new HashSet<>()).add(connection[1]);
                tunnels.computeIfAbsent(connection[1], k -> new HashSet<>()).add(connection[0]);
            }

            // Count distinct parts
            Set<String> visited = new HashSet<>();
            int distinctParts = 0;
            for (String building : buildings) {
                if (!visited.contains(building)) {
                    dfs(building, tunnels, visited);
                    distinctParts++;
                }
            }

            System.out.println(distinctParts);
        }
        scanner.close();
    }

    private static void dfs(String building, Map<String, Set<String>> tunnels, Set<String> visited) {
        visited.add(building);
        if (tunnels.containsKey(building)) {
            for (String neighbor : tunnels.get(building)) {
                if (!visited.contains(neighbor)) {
                    dfs(neighbor, tunnels, visited);
                }
            }
        }
    }
}
```

This program does the following:

1. It reads the input file "tunnels.dat".
2. For each data set:
   - It parses the buildings and tunnels from the input string.
   - It creates a graph representation of the tunnels using a Map where each building is a key and its connected buildings are the values.
   - It uses a depth-first search (DFS) to count the number of distinct parts.
   - A new part is counted each time we start a DFS from an unvisited building.

3. It prints the number of distinct parts for each data set.

The program handles all the cases mentioned in the problem statement, including:
- Data sets with no tunnels
- Tunnels that connect a building to itself
- Multiple data sets

Make sure to save this as `Tunnels.java` and have the `tunnels.dat` file in the same directory when running the program.

