To solve the problem of determining the number of distinct parts in a steam tunnel system, we can model the buildings and tunnels as a graph. Each building represents a node, and each tunnel represents an edge connecting two nodes. The task then becomes one of finding the number of connected components in this graph.

Here's a step-by-step breakdown of how we can implement the solution in Java:

1. **Parse the Input**: Read the number of datasets and then for each dataset, extract the list of buildings and the pairs of tunnels.

2. **Graph Representation**: Use an adjacency list to represent the graph. Each building will have a list of other buildings it is directly connected to via tunnels.

3. **Depth-First Search (DFS)**: Implement a DFS algorithm to explore the graph. Each time we start a DFS from an unvisited building, we have found a new connected component.

4. **Count Components**: Maintain a count of how many times we initiate a DFS, as this will correspond to the number of distinct parts.

Here is the Java code that implements the above logic:

```java
import java.io.*;
import java.util.*;

public class Tunnels {
    public static void main(String[] args) throws IOException {
        BufferedReader reader = new BufferedReader(new FileReader("tunnels.dat"));
        int N = Integer.parseInt(reader.readLine().trim());

        for (int i = 0; i < N; i++) {
            String line = reader.readLine().trim();
            String[] parts = line.split("\\},\\{");
            // Clean the parts to remove the braces
            parts[0] = parts[0].replace("{", "");
            parts[parts.length - 1] = parts[parts.length - 1].replace("}", "");
            for (int j = 1; j < parts.length; j++) {
                parts[j] = parts[j].replace("}", "").replace("{", "");
            }

            // First part is the list of buildings
            String[] buildings = parts[0].split(",");
            // Remaining parts are the tunnels
            List<String[]> tunnels = new ArrayList<>();
            for (int j = 1; j < parts.length; j++) {
                tunnels.add(parts[j].split(","));
            }

            // Create the graph
            Map<String, List<String>> graph = new HashMap<>();
            for (String building : buildings) {
                graph.put(building, new ArrayList<>());
            }
            for (String[] tunnel : tunnels) {
                graph.get(tunnel[0]).add(tunnel[1]);
                graph.get(tunnel[1]).add(tunnel[0]); // Undirected graph
            }

            // Count connected components
            Set<String> visited = new HashSet<>();
            int componentCount = 0;
            for (String building : buildings) {
                if (!visited.contains(building)) {
                    dfs(graph, building, visited);
                    componentCount++;
                }
            }

            // Output the result
            System.out.println(componentCount);
        }

        reader.close();
    }

    private static void dfs(Map<String, List<String>> graph, String building, Set<String> visited) {
        visited.add(building);
        for (String neighbor : graph.get(building)) {
            if (!visited.contains(neighbor)) {
                dfs(graph, neighbor, visited);
            }
        }
    }
}
```

