To determine if a point is inside a triangle defined by three vertices, you can use the concept of barycentric coordinates or the area method. The area method involves calculating the area of the triangle formed by the three vertices and comparing it to the sum of the areas of the triangles formed by the point and each pair of the triangle's vertices.

Here's a Java method that implements this approach:

```java
public class TrianglePointCheck {

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Example usage
        Point p1 = new Point(0, 0);
        Point p2 = new Point(5, 0);
        Point p3 = new Point(0, 5);
        Point point = new Point(1, 1);

        boolean isInside = isPointInTriangle(p1, p2, p3, point);
        System.out.println("Is the point inside the triangle? " + isInside);
    }

    public static boolean isPointInTriangle(Point p1, Point p2, Point p3, Point point) {
        double area = triangleArea(p1, p2, p3);
        double area1 = triangleArea(point, p2, p3);
        double area2 = triangleArea(p1, point, p3);
        double area3 = triangleArea(p1, p2, point);

        // Check if the sum of area1, area2, and area3 is the same as area
        return (area == area1 + area2 + area3);
    }

    private static double triangleArea(Point a, Point b, Point c) {
        return Math.abs((a.x * (b.y - c.y) + b.x * (c.y - a.y) + c.x * (a.y - b.y)) / 2.0);
    }

    static class Point {
        double x, y;

        Point(double x, double y) {
            this.x = x;
            this.y = y;
        }
    }
}
```

